Landings by Length for Georges Bank

Andy Beet

07 July, 2022

Source: vignettes/GBLandingsByLength.Rmd
GBLandingsByLength.Rmd

Goal

The ultimate goal is to create a data set that contains total annual biomass divided into size classes based on length for each of the focal species and for each fleet that targets them. The resulting table will have a format similar to:

Fleet Area Year Species Biomass sizeclass1 sizeclass2 sizeclass3 sizeclass4 sizeclass5
1 1 1964 1 222 0 0.05 0.25 0.5 0.25
1 1 1965 1 345 0 0.05 0.25 0.5 0.25
1 1 1966 1 343 0 0.05 0.25 0.5 0.25
1 1 1964 2 2137 0 0.05 0.25 0.5 0.25
1 1 1965 2 678 0 0.05 0.25 0.5 0.25
1 1 1966 2 346 0 0.05 0.25 0.5 0.25

Columns with the format sizeclassx represent the xth size class. A size class is defined by a range of lengths (cm) and its width is dependent on the species. Size classes were based on life history traits. For the focal species, the widths of each size class are defined in the following table (subject to change):

sizeclass1 sizeclass2 sizeclass3 sizeclass4 sizeclass5 species_itis
SPINY DOGFISH 20 20 20 20 30 160617
WINTER SKATE 20 20 20 20 40 564145
ATLANTIC HERRING 5 5 5 5 20 161722
ATLANTIC COD 20 20 20 40 50 164712
HADDOCK 10 10 20 20 20 164744
YELLOWTAIL FLOUNDER 10 10 10 10 20 172909
WINTER FLOUNDER 10 10 10 10 10 172905
ATLANTIC MACKEREL 10 10 10 10 10 172414
SILVER HAKE 10 10 10 10 30 164791
GOOSEFISH 20 20 20 30 40 164499

For example, the first size class for SPINY DOGFISH is [0-20] cm, the second class is (20-40] cm, …, the 5 size class is (80-110] cm.

Data and methods

Commercial fisheries landings were pulled using R package comlandr

The length data were pulled from the stockeff.mv_cf_len table

The package mscatch is used to facilitate these data pulls.

For each species, a set of rules are applied (similar to the approach taken in a stock assessment), to determine how the landings and discard data are aggregated based on the availability of length samples. Biomass is then estimated for each LENGTH (1 cm bins) category by YEAR and . This data set is exported in the package as realFisheryLencomp

Detailed methods can be found in the mscatch package
